Here is an example of a program that uses dynamic programming to find the n-th Fibonacci number in C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int fib(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return 0;
    if (n == 1) return 1;
    int result = fib(n-1);
    result = (result + fib(n-2)) % 1000000007; //modulus to make the result an integer
    return result;
}
int main() {
    cout << fib(34) << endl; // should print 557496987
}
```
This program uses dynamic programming to calculate the n-th Fibonacci number by recursively calling itself until the desired number is reached. It stores the results of each recursion in a table, which allows it to quickly calculate the next number in the sequence without having to calculate the previous ones again. The modulus operation ensures that the result is an integer.

